'''Rescue – The British Archaeological Trust''' is a charitable organisation in the United Kingdom. It was founded in 1971 as a [[pressure group]] by a team including the archaeologists [[Margaret Ursula Jones]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2001/may/02/guardianobituaries.education|title=Margaret Jones|date=2001-05-02|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-08-05}}</ref> and [[Philip A. Barker|Phillip A. Barker]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fagan|first1=Brian M.|title=The Great Archaeologists|date=2014|publisher=Thames & Hudson|isbn=9780500772379|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oQg7CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT245&lpg=PT245&dq=Philip+A.+Barker+rescue&source=bl&ots=FAKP6_JvFB&sig=SoZHKJ_A9eY4nLm0tPJA0YF9qIs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjqmM6WlOnZAhVKnFkKHS3rAeM4ChDoAQg9MAY#v=onepage&q=Philip%20A.%20Barker%20rescue&f=false|accessdate=13 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>

The Trust campaigns for government funds to permit the excavation of archaeological sites in advance of road-building, construction or other development. Specific actions include opposing the planned tunnel near the site of [[Stonehenge]], proposed in 2017, claiming that it could threaten the site's [[UNESCO|UNESCO heritage]] status,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Browne|first1=Dom|title=Stonehenge tunnel plans modified as costs increase|url=https://www.transport-network.co.uk/Stonehenge-tunnel-plans-modified-as-costs-increase/14456|website=transport-network.co.uk|accessdate=13 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> and criticising the use of [[metal detector]]s to discover items of cultural significance.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Owen|first1=Jonathan|title=Anger as TV show endorses metal-detecting 'plunderers'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/tv-radio/anger-as-tv-show-endorsesmetal-detecting-plunderers-2260814.html|website=The Independent|accessdate=13 March 2018|date=3 April 2011}}</ref>


