{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2012}} {{Use British English|date=August 2012}} '''Richard Grunberger''' (7 March 1924 [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] – 15 February 2005) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] historian, who specialised in study of the [[Third Reich]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Nazi psychoanalysis|first=Laurence A. |last=Rickels|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|year= 2002|ISBN= 0-8166-3697-4|pages=12}}</ref><ref name="Rothenberg">{{cite news | last = Rothenberg | first = Ruth | title = Obituary: Richard Grunberger | publisher = [[The Guardian]] | date = 2005-05-07 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/may/07/guardianobituaries.obituaries | accessdate = 2009-08-25 }}</ref>
He was born in Austria to [[Jewish]] parents. After the 1938 [[Anschluss]] with [[Nazi Germany|Hitler's Germany]], he was put on the first [[Kindertransport]] train to leave [[Vienna]]. He was initially housed in a [[refugee]] camp at [[Lowestoft]] in [[England]]. After this he lived with a Jewish family, who were West End tailors in [[London]]. Grunberger entered their tailoring business. His desire for education however led to his taking A levels at [[Birkbeck, University of London|Birkbeck college]]. He gained an [[Exhibitioner|exhibition]] scholarship in history at [[King's College London]].<ref name = "Rothenberg"/>
When he went to the [[Wiener Library]] in London, he expressed to a friend his frustration at the absence of a book that held together the masses of documentation surrounding [[Nazism]] and 20th-century [[Germany]]. A friend asked why he did not write one, and so he did. The product was ''A Social History of the Third Reich'', first published in 1971 by Weidenfeld & Nicolson. It has since become a significant text for studying the social history of Nazi Germany in schools and at undergraduate level.<ref name = "Rothenberg"/>
Initially, much of Grunberger's leisure time in Britain was taken up by the [[communist]] youth group [[Communist Youth of Austria — Young Left|Young Austria]]. In spite of this, his political outlook was [[social democratic]].<ref name = "Rothenberg"/>
