{{Distinguish|Paul B. Coremans}}
{{Infobox writer | name = Victor Amédée Jacques Marie Coremans | image = | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1802|10|05}} | birth_place = [[Brussels]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1872|10|23|1802|10|05}} | death_place = [[Ixelles]] | resting_place = | occupation = Archivist, journalist, scholar | language = German | residence = | nationality = Belgium | education = | alma_mater = | period = | subjects = Politics, culture, history | notableworks = {{unbulleted list|''Die Stimme aus dem Kerker''|''Kerkerblumen''|''Die göttlichen Befreier''}} }}
'''Victor Amédée Jacques Marie Coremans''' (5 October 1802 – 23 October 1872) was a Belgian [[archivist]], [[journalist]], [[historian]], and [[political activist]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Cuvelier |first=J. |editor=Académie royale des sciences, des lettres et des beaux-arts de Belgique |title=Biographie Nationale, Vol. XXIX |location=Brussels |publisher=Émile Bruylant|date=1956 |oclc=65751192 |pages=481–486 |language=French |url=http://www.academieroyale.be/academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2088.pdf}}</ref> He supported the [[Flemish Movement]], advocating nationhood for [[Flanders]].
==Life and career== Victor was born in [[Brussels]] on 5 October 1802, the son of Jacques-Jean Coremans, a judge, and Anne-Marie Vandersande.<ref name="liberaalarchief">{{cite web |url=http://www.liberaalarchief.be/C.html |title=De Blauwe Wie is Wie |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=liberaalarchief.be |publisher=[[Liberal Archive (Belgium)|Liberal Archive]] |language=Dutch |accessdate=12 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114091231/http://www.liberaalarchief.be/C.html |archive-date=14 January 2014 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 1821 he was banished from Vienna for sedition.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} 1824 he edited the 'Erlanger Zeitung'. From 1831 to 1832, while living in Munich, he published and edited the [[Nuremberg]] radical newspaper ''Die Freie Presse'' (The Free Press).<ref>''Die Freie Presse'' 1831. [https://books.google.com/books?id=5H5EAAAAcAAJ Available on Google Books]</ref> The Bavarian authorities responded by laying political charges on him, for which he was imprisoned.<ref name="bibliophile">{{cite book |title=Le bibliophile belge, Volume 12 : Histoire des livres—Essai d'un dictionnaire des ouvrages anonymes et pseudonymes publiés en belgique |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ew4_AAAAcAAJ&pg=PA302 |pages=302–303 |language=French |access-date=2017-04-25 |via=Google Books}}</ref> While in prison he wrote three German-language books that were well-received in Germany: ''Die Stimme aus dem Kerker'' (The Voice from the Dungeon), ''Kerkerblumen'' (Dungeon Flowers), and ''Die göttlichen Befreier'' (The Divine Liberator).<ref name="bibliophile"/>
After his release he spent some time in Switzerland before returning to his native Belgium. On 13 April 1836, he was appointed to the newly created ''[[Commission royale d'Histoire]]'' in Brussels. He went on to become the curator of the German collection in the [[National Archives of Belgium]], and to publish several more works.<ref name="bibliophile"/>
His scholarly writing addressed various topics in the history, culture, and politics of [[Belgium]], Germany, and [[Austria]]. He published scholarly pieces in the ''Bulletin de la Commission royale d'histoire'' (1844–1847) and in the ''Revue d'histoire et d'archéologie'' (1860–1863). One article examined the origins and permutations of the legendary monarch [[Gambrinus]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Coremans |first=Victor Amédée Jacques Marie |year=1842 |title=Note sur la tradition de Gambrivius roi mythique de Flandre par le docteur Coremans |journal=Bulletin de la Commission royale d'histoire |volume=5 |pages=378–388 |language=French |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yhw0AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA379 |accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref> However, throughout his later he continued to promote [[liberal nationalism]], and especially [[Flemish Movement|Flemish nationhood]], through this journalistic writing. These articles were published in such journals as ''Vlaamsch België'', ''De Noordstar'', and ''De Zweep''.
On 7 August 1872, he retired from the National Archives. He died in [[Ixelles]] on 23 October 1872.<ref name="liberaalarchief"/>
